<dl id="n10063c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10063c">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10063c"> 63(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> kingscouriered <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10063c"><li>FW 471.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qC/lexqC.htm#n10063c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qC/l39qC.htm#n10063c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10063c">MS BL 47482b-33</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:067 <a name="qA2d" href="../../FF/fdra/qda.htm#qC2d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/q/qC2d.htm#n10063c">Draft: III&sect;2C.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">L&apos;historien byzantin Chalcondyle, qui vivait au XV<sup>e</sup> si&egrave;cle, raconte que les courriers turcs, dont les chevaux &eacute;taient fatigu&eacute;s, avaient pour consigne de d&eacute;monter le premier cavalier venu et de prendre son cheval, le service de Sa Hautesse le padischah devant passer avant tout. <font color="green">[The Byzantine historian Chalcondyle, who lived in the 15th Century, wrote that Turkish couriers whose horses were tired were instructed to make the first rider to pass by dismount and take his horse since the service of His Highness the Pasha comes before everything else.]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 235-6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
